The paper discusses the effectiveness of automated tests in detecting faults introduced during changes in software, which is a key concern in software engineering (cs.SE). The study focuses on Java projects, which suggests a focus on programming languages and compilers (cs.PL). The paper also evaluates the validity of code coverage as a measure for test effectiveness, which is related to software verification and validation (cs.SW). The study uses an extreme mutation testing approach, which involves generating many variations of the code to test the effectiveness of the tests, which could fall under machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the study assesses the impact of the ratio of pseudo-tested methods on the software project, which could be related to security and cryptography (cs.CR).
